column1: Before 1 January 2023, will the presidents of Russia and Ukraine meet in person?
column6: ['Foreign Policy', 'Security and Conflict', 'Non-US Politics']
Moved to 0 given only 4 days left.
Not in the next few days.

Since there is less than one week remaining before the period in question ends and there is no meeting currently planned, the war rages as ever and close to none diplomatic efforts are made, the probability of an in person meeting between the presidents is highly unlikely.
Given the tension + lack of time, believe the probability is <0.5%

I don't think this is going to happen. If they were to meet the only chance I might see this happen is the coming up G20 Summit in Indonesia by "bumbing accidently into each other". And this asumes that both are attending. For Putin to come to the G20, I give it a chance of 18%. Putin has only leaft Russia on few occasions and met with other country leaders, which are at least on paper on Russia's side and in close proximity to Russia. So I don't he is willing to risk to have to confront a bunch of other country leaders, which are openly supporting Ukraine to various degrees, if they are actually willing to meet up him. It might be different, if Putin ceases to be Russian president but then it depends who would succeed, is it somebody from the war monger camp or somebody from the fraction which seriously wants to end this war. And the whole succession scenerio in my estimate has to unfold in a way that the next Russian president and the whole Kremlin crowd have by then sorted and realigned their allegiances and rivalries. This still would be a black box in peaceful times and this is Russia, so anything can happen and nothing is for certain. For Zelensky to attend something like a 4%. I don't think he is going to leave Ukraine as long fighting is continueing. I would say as a rule of thumb, Zelensky is not going abroard until it is safe to fly in and out of Ukraine. In case Zelensky ceases to be Ukrainian president (which only can mean sudden death or serious illness) not so much would change in that circumstances, cause the Ukrainians pretty much seem in consent there are no talks with the Russian side unless the Russians are out of the country or showing their willingness to retreat back over the internationally recognized border. So that makes 0.0072% that are both there. But nevertheless I make it generously 2%, because you know: It's Russia: You never know so anything can happen. And propably more important: I wanna be able to say (as a small ego treat): I saw the black swan when it still was in the black box.
Putin's ground war grinds on. No one appears to believe Russia's troop mobilization will change the war's trajectory; least of all, the Russians.

Helpful rationales below. I think the probability is <1% by the question deadline. There is not proper set up for such a meeting, and nothing to gain for each side at this point. Only downside risk.

I reduced my forecast by 1% to be now 2%....with it falling in the future as we get closer to 1 January, as well as taking into account that Russia just appointed Surovikin the new GO in charge of the "special operation". I believe Russia will want to give him a few weeks to months to see if a more aggressive campaign will change the tide of the operation. Since military position often influences final diplomatic outcomes, Russia wants to see if it can improve its position while Ukraine, backed by continued confirmation that the US and allies will continue to provide military and financial support, means that Ukraine won't be brought to the settlement table anytime soon. While this could change if Russia uses a tactical nuclear weapon, I think it would strengthen Ukrainian resolve. Some "game changers" I see that might change this forecast would be if: 1) President Z is killed 2) If Putin is killed 3) if Belarus comes into the war effort on Russia's side 4) Russia violates NATO's territory and NATO gets involved.
Putin’s options for pressing on with this war are narrowing, with that the option of meeting with A representative of Ukraine rise.
I believe there is next to zero chance of this happening. This would only happen if one side was ready to concede AND the president of Russia isn't Vladimir Putin.

Running out of time, and see no indication that either Russia or Ukraine are inclined to end the war soon. Leaving at 5% because less than that is where I set my own noise floor.

With Ukraine's success on the battlefield, and President Z. saying that if Russia annexes the four Ukrainian regions, that diplomacy would be off the table, I don't see President Z. meeting with President Putin. I don't see this changing even if a nuclear weapon is used by Russia. The only way I can see Ukraine meeting with Russia is if a cease-fire is called (unlikely, but possible due to a winter stalemate) or if Putin is no longer in office. Of note, the prompt's article references are either older (from summer, before the successful counter-offensive, or don't say that President Z. will meet with Putin.)

I would project that the probability of a meeting between the two leaders would be slim-to-none before the New Year. Just yesterday, occupation officials in the south and eastern parts of Ukraine (which identify strongly as ethnically Russian) announced they were putting together a referendum to make formal aceeding (peace) agreements with Russia. This puts them one step closer to annexation, which Putin would likely use to fuel further military volunteerism (or forced service) from the new "Russian" territory, as well as allow for Russian troops to further mobilize throughout the region. Since Zelensky has stated several times since the fighting began that there can be no peace talks until Russia removes its military forces from Ukraine's borders, I would consider it highly improbable that the two meet barring unforeseen circumstances that lead to either the complete withdrawal of Russian forces or the outright defeat of Ukrainian forces in the war.
Putin moves as of today escalating rather than agreeing mode, a meeting between the two sides in the near future seems more unlikely than ever. Full tilt.
Possible that the new announcement will lead to reconsideration by Ukraine

Base rate: peace talks in war times, if no side is close to defeat and no side has reached their goals and no side is overpowering the other side: <1% under current conditions. None of the countries is projected to run out of resources in the next 3 months, none is projected to reach their goals or are close to be defeated or overpowered.

Kyiv has stated that "negotiations" may only continue if troops are withdrawn from true Ukrainian territory. "negotiations" implies at least a meeting, including an in-person one, however, given Russia's stance on not withdrawing troops, this would then make this meeting at least not possible within the next three months. This was in response to Erdogan's openness to hold a meeting in Turkey for the leaders.

Kremlin has stated such meeting will only occur if/when a peace agreement is signed as of April 2022 (https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/kremlin-says-putin-zelenskiy-meeting-only-possible-once-document-is-agreed-2022-04-05/)

Timeline too short for hostilities to ratchet down/cease. Even if cease-fire negotiated, territorial issues too complicated to be resolved in this timeframe. Putin (or successor) would not want to give Ukraine the status of a head of state to head of state meeting without concessions that would be unacceptable to Ukraine.
I believe that mediators will meet, but not the head of states
No, not enough time for either arrangements to be made or for the Russian leadership to chance to one who wouldn't require elaborate arrangements to be made.
Only if leadership in Russia changes.

This would be very dependent on how poorly the war continues for Russia. Zelensky has repeatedly stated his terms and his openness to peace but Putin has been inconsistent since the war's beginning. The Russian government is currently unlikely to come back to the bargaining table. Should the Ukrainians manage to take back Crimea and the Novorossiyan territories of Donetsk and Luhansk, the chances are significantly better. Should the Ukrainians not invade Russian territory afterwards I think it would be more likely for talks. If Russia is actually invaded, I believe the Russian government will drastically escalate the war instead of negotiating.

The war between Russia and Ukraine is tragically for the world and should have had never started by Russia from my point view. Russia is sending constantly signals that is open for negotiations. The Ukraine is not sovereign by opinion of Russia. The Ukraine is also not sovereign as retainer of The West due to fact, that about 5 Billion US$ it is missing per month on state budget, due to fact that about 7 million Ukrainians live off EU countries budgets, due to fact that has not enough weapons, due to fact it has no weapon industry due to fact that about 80% of its BIP are located at occupied areas of Russia, due to fact that only by intelligence of USA it can survive in this war. I assume if the NATO Nations may press the Ukraine for negotiations they will happen immediately, because after 4 weeks the Ukraine is running out of all resources it needs to go ahead to fight this war. Therefore the President of USA, UK and some Members of NATO decide when the negotiations may begin from Ukraine side. This may happen soon in the next months like a probability of a falling coin by economic evaluations of the supporting countries. At the end of the day the Ukraine may need several hundreds billion for reconstruction. That will have to delivered by the West because the Ukraine has nothing of value anymore and Russia is a superpower and will not pay anything but the blood of its military personnel.

Leaders of nations at war have met in person before the cessation of hostilities throughout history to negotiate. Usually it occurs near the end of a conflict. Both nations are not showing signs of giving into the conflict and have only given unreasonable demands to resume negotiations (unreasonable as determined by the other side). Although negotiations can occur quickly, negotiations usually take a matter of weeks or months. The current conditions are stable enough to keep the conflict going without negotiations for some time. However, conditions could change that would lead to bringing one side to the table more quickly which increases the chances of this occurring. Both men are invited to the G20 Summit in Indonesia in November setting up a possible opportunity.

From Zelensky's perspective suggesting this kind of meeting is a relatively harm free thing to do since it works to suggest he is looking to an end a war that he didn't start. However it's hard to see how Putin could position himself to take such a meeting domestically and internationally. On one hand domestically he could use it to A) show he's trying to be reasonable and B) actually make no concessions, however this would be problematic for him if he were then to find Russia losing entirely and being forced out of the country. I suspect that domestically there isn't much to be gained at this point unless the talks result in some concessions from the Ukraine side, but it certainly doesn't feel like negotiation from a position of strength from Russia's perspective. I also suspect if Zelensky sees the talks as positive for Putin either domestically or internationally, he will not actually go for it.
Perhaps at the G20. But either Putin sends Lawrow or cancels his attendance, because of the russophobic tendency of most world leaders.

I can't picture it, but I won't completely rule it out. I think the real chance is <0.1%, though.(I have a hard time picturing the level of self control it would take for Zelensky to sit at a long table with Putin.)
I doubt they will meet in person in such a short time- President Zelensky has said it that while He supports this idea, it is also quite difficult to arrange said meeting with President Putin.
No indications of negotiation/settlement/peace talks as of yet.
I'm skeptical the meeting will occur, Putin's agreeing to meet with Zelensky would be an admission of failure of his original goal.
No chance! It would be a miracle if they even communicated about something constructive before then. Things are waaaayyyy off anything even vaguely like a reason for them to talk let alone meet.

Right now Volodymyr Zelensky must take every precaution necessary to protect his life, and meeting with Putin and other Russian officials leaves him vulnerable to an attack. Furthermore, it is unlikely that an in-person meeting would achieve anything as it would expose Putin to outside jurisdiction as well. If anything, I imagine the two of them could meet via a phone call or virtual communication service, as both Ukraine and Russia will eventually need to end the war going on in the region. Consequently, Russia's weakness has been exposed to the world, and it is getting more and more likely that they will need to seek a route that does not involve keeping military forces in Ukraine. However, an in-person meeting is completely out of the question and I don't think the two of them will ever be in the same room.

Agree with @MrLittleTexas Under what scenario would a meeting like this take place? I believe this war will not end with a negotiated settlement. We don't know Ukraine's military objectives, but I believe it's to reclaim every inch of territory lost to Russia since 2014 (an 'unconditional defeat' scenario for Russia). I don't believe Zelensky would meet with Putin to sign a treaty capitulating any Ukrainian territory, and Putin certainly wouldn't meet with Zelensky to sign anything indicating a Russian defeat. Under that scenario there's no treaty; just status quo ante.
I find it very hard to imagine a short term scenario where this happens. Perhaps if there is an unexpected change of leadership in one or both countries?
